      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics argue that originalism is merely a thin veil for judicial activism, but proponents counter that this critique fundamentally misunderstands the doctrine. Originalism doesn't demand judges adopt their personal feelings; rather, it demands they adhere to the objective, ascertainable meaning of the text as understood by the public at the time of ratification. To suggest otherwise is to argue that judges should simply legislate from the bench, which is the very definition of judicial tyranny.",
