      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument that originalism blocks modern rights is a common liberal critique, but it ignores the foundational principles of the Constitution itself. The Founders deliberately created broad, structural protections, like the Due Process Clause, precisely to allow for evolving understandings of liberty. Originalism doesn't freeze society; it anchors the law to a stable, legitimate source, preventing judges from imposing transient, subjective political whims onto the nation.",
